    "created_at": "2022-07-08T04:26:36Z",
    "updated_at": "2022-07-08T04:26:36Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Probably not going to be telling you anything you don't already know, but just want to +1 that I've encountered these same issues and this is something that I think is going to be a hard blocker for many JavaScript developers wanting to use Hardhat. The integration is difficult enough that a lot of people will decide to say screw it and swap out a piece of the stack.\r\n\r\nIt's not impossible, of course, but you need to create a clean boundary between the parts of the project that are CommonJS (Hardhat) versus the parts of the project that are ESM (everything else). You almost need a monorepo tool to pull it off at which point you've stopped being a tool that makes devs life easier and have become one that makes it harder.\r\n\r\n> See [this StackOverflow issue](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/70714785/use-hardhat-es5-together-with-sveltekit-es6) for a thorough description of why finding a workable solution with SvelteKit today is nearly impossible. I was [able to get Astro working](https://github.com/ajcwebdev/taking-astro-to-the-moon) by changing `astro.config.js` to `astro.config.mjs` and omitting `type` in `package.json` but SvelteKit doesn't like `svelte.config.mjs` for some reason.\r\n\r\nIf a developer has already decided they want a particular metaframework that is based on ESM (which is going to be almost all of them in the next year or two) then the decision to use a different tool that won't completely blow up your build tooling like Foundry becomes almost a given.\r\n\r\nI totally agree that adding ESM support is more complex than almost anyone realizes unless they've had to migrate a framework from CommonJS to ESM. But if adding proper ESM support is going to be a long ways out (like more than 2 or 3 months), then I'd recommend providing a boilerplate example app to address this issue.\r\n\r\nIt would need to be built with the assumption that the frontend has its own cleanly separated repo from the Hardhat project files where are in their own different repo. Sounds like @cagrigit-hub already has a working implementation and you should jump at the opportunity to make that official.",
